# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: festschrift
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] An **abstract** is a brief summary of a research article, thesis, review, conference proceeding, or any in-depth analysis of a particular subject and is often used to help the reader quickly ascertain the paper's purpose.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] When used, an abstract always appears at the beginning of a manuscript or typescript, acting as the point-of-entry for any given academic paper or patent application.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Abstracting and indexing services for various academic disciplines are aimed at compiling a body of literature for that particular subject.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The terms ***précis*** or ***synopsis*** are used in some publications to refer to the same thing that other publications might call an "abstract".
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] In management reports, an *executive summary* usually contains more information (and often more sensitive information) than the abstract does.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Academic literature uses the abstract to succinctly communicate complex research.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] An abstract may act as a stand-alone entity instead of a full paper.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] As such, an abstract is used by many organizations as the basis for selecting research that is proposed for presentation in the form of a poster, platform/oral presentation or workshop presentation at an academic conference.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Most bibliographic databases only index abstracts rather than providing the entire text of the paper.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Full texts of scientific papers must often be purchased because of copyright and/or publisher fees and therefore the abstract is a significant selling point for the reprint or electronic form of the full text.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The abstract can convey the main results and conclusions of a scientific article but the full text article must be consulted for details of the methodology, the full experimental results, and a critical discussion of the interpretations and conclusions.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Abstracts are occasionally inconsistent with full reports.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] This has the potential to mislead clinicians who rely solely on the information present in the abstract without consulting the full report.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] An abstract allows one to sift through copious numbers of papers for ones in which the researcher can have more confidence that they will be relevant to their research.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Once papers are chosen based on the abstract, they must be read carefully to be evaluated for relevance.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] It is generally agreed that one must not base reference citations on the abstract alone, but the content of an entire paper.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] This is because abstracts may not be fully representative of the full report or article.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Therefore, basing reference citations solely on the information present in the abstract could be misleading.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] According to the results of a study published in *PLOS Medicine*, the "exaggerated and inappropriate coverage of research findings in the news media" is ultimately related to inaccurately reporting or over-interpreting research results in many abstract conclusions.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The history of abstracting dates back to the point when it was felt necessary to summarise the content of documents in order to make the information contained in them more accessible.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] In Mesopotamia during the early second millennium BCE, clay envelopes designed to protect enclosed cuneiform documents from tampering were inscribed either with the full text of the document or a summary.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] In the Greco-Roman world, many texts were abstracted: summaries of non-fiction works were known as epitomes, and in many cases the only information about works which have not survived to modernity comes from their epitomes which have survived.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Similarly, the text of many ancient Greek and Roman plays commenced with a hypothesis which summed up the play's plot.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Non-literary documents were also abstracted: the Tebtunis papyri found in the Ancient Egyptian town of Tebtunis contain abstracts of legal documents.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] During the Middle Ages, the pages of scholarly texts contained summaries of their contents as marginalia, as did some manuscripts of the Code of Justinian.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The use of abstracts to summarise science originates in the early 1800s, when the secretary of the Royal Society would record brief summaries of talks into the minutes of each meeting, which were referred to as 'abstracts'.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The Royal Society abstracts from 1800 – 1837 were later collated and published in the society's journal *Philosophical Transactions*, with the first group appearing in 1832.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] These abstracts were generally one or more pages long.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Other learned societies adopted similar practices.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The RAS abstracts were between one and three paragraphs long.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] In both cases, these early abstracts were written by the learned society, not the author of the paper.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Perhaps the earliest example of an abstract published alongside the paper it summarises was the 1919 paper *On the Irregularities of Motion of the Foucault Pendulum* published in the *Physical Review* of the American Physical Society, which often published abstracts thereafter.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Abstracts in the United States are protected under copyright law just as any other form of written speech is protected.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Abstract is often expected to tell a complete story of the paper, as for most readers, abstract is the only part of the paper that will be read.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] It should allow the reader to give an elevator pitch of the full paper.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] It may also contain brief references, although some publications' standard style omits references from the abstract, reserving them for the article body (which, by definition, treats the same topics but in more depth).
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Abstract length varies by discipline and publisher requirements.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Typical length ranges from 100 to 500 words, but very rarely more than a page and occasionally just a few words.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] An abstract may or may not have the section title of "abstract" explicitly listed as an antecedent to content.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Sometimes, abstracts are sectioned logically as an overview of what appears in the paper, with any of the following subheadings: Background, Introduction, Objectives, Methods, Results, Discussion, Conclusions.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Abstracts in which these subheadings are explicitly given are often called **structured abstracts**.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Abstracts that comprise one paragraph (no explicit subheadings) are often called **unstructured abstracts**.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Abstracts are important enough that IMRAD is even sometimes recast as AIMRAD.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The **informative abstract**, also known as the **complete abstract**, is a compendious summary of a paper's substance and its background, purpose, methodology, results, and conclusion.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Usually between 100 and 200 words, the informative abstract summarizes the paper's structure, its major topics and key points.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] A format for scientific short reports that is similar to an informative abstract has been proposed in recent years.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Informative abstracts may be viewed as standalone documents.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The **descriptive abstract**, also known as the **limited abstract** or the **indicative abstract**, provides a description of what the paper covers without delving into its substance.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] A descriptive abstract is akin to a table of contents in paragraph form.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] During the late 2000s, due to the influence of computer storage and retrieval systems such as the Internet, some scientific publications, primarily those published by Elsevier, started including graphical abstracts alongside the text abstracts.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The graphic is intended to summarize or be an exemplar for the main thrust of the article.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] It is not intended to be as exhaustive a summary as the text abstract, rather it is supposed to indicate the type, scope, and technical coverage of the article at a glance.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] The use of graphical abstracts has been generally well received by the scientific community.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Moreover, some journals also include video abstracts and animated abstracts made by the authors to easily explain their papers.
[src:festschrift/abstract-summary] Various methods can be used to evaluate abstract quality, e.g. rating by readers, checklists, and readability measures (such as Flesch Reading Ease).
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Before the advent of the Internet, it was difficult for scholars to distribute articles giving their research results.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Historically publishers performed services including proofreading, typesetting, copy editing, printing, and worldwide distribution.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In modern times all researchers became expected to give the publishers digital copies of their work which needed no further processing.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For digital distribution printing was unnecessary, copying was free, and worldwide distribution happens online instantly.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In science journal publishing, Internet technology enabled the Big Five major scientific publishers—Elsevier, Springer, Wiley, Taylor and Francis and American Chemical Society—to cut their expenditures such that they could consistently generate profits of over 35% per year.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In 2017 these five published 56% of all journal articles.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The remaining 44% were published by over 200 small publishers.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The Internet made it easier for researchers to do work which had previously been done by publishers, and some people began to feel that they did not need to pay for the services of publishers.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] This perception was a problem for publishers, who stated that their services were still necessary at the rates they asked.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Critics began to describe publishers' practices with terms such as "corporate scam" and "racket".
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Scholars sometimes obtain articles from fellow scholars through unofficial channels, such as posting requests on Twitter using the hashtag "#icanhazpdf" (a play on the I Can Has Cheezburger? meme), to avoid paying publishers' access charges.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In 2004, there were reports in British media of a "revolution in academic publishing" which would make research freely available online but many scientists continued to publish their work in the traditional big name journals like *Nature*.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For a short time in 2012, the name Academic Spring, inspired by the Arab Spring, was used to indicate movements by academics, researchers, and scholars opposing the restrictive copyright and circulation of traditional academic journals and promoting free access online instead.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The barriers to free access for recent scientific research became a hot topic in 2012, after a blog post by mathematician Timothy Gowers went viral in January.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] According to the *Financial Times*, the movement was named by Dennis Johnson of Melville House Publishing, though scientist Mike Taylor has suggested the name came from *The Economist*.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Mike Taylor argued that the Academic Spring may have some unexpected results beyond the obvious benefits.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Referring to work by the biophysicist Cameron Neylon, he says that, because modern science is now more dependent on well-functioning networks than individuals, making information freely available may help computer-based analyses to provide opportunities for major scientific breakthroughs.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Government and university officials have welcomed the prospect of saving on subscriptions which have been rising in cost, while universities' budgets have been shrinking.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Mark Walport, the director of Wellcome Trust, has indicated that science sponsors do not mind having to fund publication in addition to the research.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Although it has some historical precedent, open access became desired in response to the advent of electronic publishing as part of a broader desire for academic journal publishing reform.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Electronic publishing created new benefits as compared to paper publishing but beyond that, it contributed to causing problems in traditional publishing models.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Rather than applying traditional notions of copyright to academic publications, readers should be free to build upon the research of others.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Publications should be libre or "free to build upon".
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Everyone should have greater awareness of the serious social problems caused by restricting access to academic research.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Everyone should recognize that there are serious economic challenges for the future of academic publishing.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Even though open access models are problematic, traditional publishing models definitely are not sustainable and something radical needs to change immediately.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Moore proposes designing multiple infrastructural interventions to facilitate experiments in collectivity.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Open access also has ambitions beyond merely granting access to academic publications, as access to research is only a tool for helping people achieve other goals.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Open access advances scholarly pursuits in the fields of open data, open government, open educational resources, free and open-source software, and open science, among others.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The motivations for academic journal publishing reform include the ability of computers to store large amounts of information, the advantages of giving more researchers access to preprints, and the potential for interactivity between researchers.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Various studies showed that the demand for open access research was such that freely available articles consistently had impact factors which were higher than articles published under restricted access.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Some universities reported that modern "package deal" subscriptions were too costly for them to maintain, and that they would prefer to subscribe to journals individually to save money.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The problems which led to discussion about academic publishing reform have been considered in the context of what provision of open access might provide.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The pricing crisis does not only mean strain to budgets, but also that researchers actually are losing access to journals.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Not even the wealthiest libraries in the world are able to afford all the journals that their users are demanding, and less rich libraries are severely harmed by lack of access to journals.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Libraries are cutting their book budgets to pay for academic journals.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Libraries do not own electronic journals in permanent archival form as they do paper copies, so if they have to cancel a subscription then they lose all subscribed journals.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] This did not happen with paper journals, and yet costs historically have been higher for electronic versions.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Academic publishers get essential assets from their subscribers in a way that other publishers do not.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Authors donate the texts of academic journals to the publishers and grant rights to publish them, and editors and referees donate peer-review to validate the articles.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The people writing the journals are questioning the increased pressure put upon them to pay higher prices for the journal produced by their community.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Conventional publishers are using a business model which requires access barriers and creates artificial scarcity.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] All publishers need revenue, but open access promises models in which scarcity is fundamental to raising revenue.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Scholarly publishing depends heavily on government policy, public subsidies, gift economy, and anti-competitive practices, yet all of these things are in conflict with the conventional academic publishing model of restricting access to works.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Toll access journals compete more for authors to donate content to them than they compete for subscribers to pay for the work.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] This is because every scholarly journal has a natural monopoly over the information of its field.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Because of this, the market for pricing journals does not have feedback because it is outside of traditional market forces, and the prices have no control to drive it to serve the needs of the market.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Besides the natural monopoly, there is supporting evidence that prices are artificially inflated to benefit publishers while harming the market.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Evidence includes the trend of large publishers to have accelerating prices increases greater than small publishers, when in traditional markets high volume and high sales enables cost savings and lower prices.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Conventional publishers fund "content protection" actions which restrict and police content sharing.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For-profit publishers have economic incentives to decrease rates of rejected articles so that they publish more content to sell.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] No such market force exists if selling content for money is not a motivating factor.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Many researchers are unaware that it might be possible for them to have all the research articles they need, and just accept it as fate that they will always be without some of the articles they would like to read.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Access to toll-access journals is not scaling with increases in research and publishing, and the academic publishers are under market forces to restrict increases in publishing and indirectly because of that they are restricting the growth of research.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Publishers state that if profit was not a consideration in the pricing of journals then the cost of accessing those journals would not substantially change.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Publishers also state that they add value to publications in many ways, and without academic publishing as an institution the readership would miss these services and fewer people would have access to articles.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Critics of open access have suggested that by itself, this is not a solution to scientific publishing's most serious problem – it simply changes the paths through which ever-increasing sums of money flow.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Evidence for this does exist and for example, Yale University ended its financial support of BioMed Central's Open Access Membership program effective July 27, 2007.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Opponents of the open access model see publishers as a part of the scholarly information chain and view a pay-for-access model as being necessary in ensuring that publishers are adequately compensated for their work.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Scholarly journal publishers that support pay-for-access claim that the "gatekeeper" role they play, maintaining a scholarly reputation, arranging for peer review, and editing and indexing articles, require economic resources that are not supplied under an open access model.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Conventional journal publishers may also lose customers to open access publishers who compete with them.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The Partnership for Research Integrity in Science and Medicine (PRISM), a lobbying organization formed by the Association of American Publishers (AAP), is opposed to the open access movement.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] PRISM and AAP have lobbied against the increasing trend amongst funding organizations to require open publication, describing it as "government interference" and a threat to peer review.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For researchers, publishing an article in a reputable scientific journal is perceived as being beneficial to one's reputation among scientific peers and in advancing one's academic career.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] There is a concern that the perception of open access journals do not have the same reputation, which will lead to less publishing.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Park and Qin discuss the perceptions that academics have with regard to open access journals.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Journal article authors are generally not directly financially compensated for their work beyond their institutional salaries and the indirect benefits that an enhanced reputation provides in terms of institutional funding, job offers, and peer collaboration.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] There are those, for example PRISM, who think that open access is unnecessary or even harmful.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] David Goodman argued that there is no need for those outside major academic institutions to have access to primary publications, at least in some fields.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For instance in Australia, 80% of research funding comes through taxes, whereas in Japan and Switzerland, only approximately 10% is from the public coffers.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For various reasons open access journals have been established by predatory publishers who seek to use the model to make money without regard to producing a quality journal.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The causes of predatory open access publishing include the low barrier to creating the appearance of a legitimate digital journal and funding models which may include author publishing costs rather than subscription sales.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] University librarian Jeffrey Beall published a "List of Predatory Publishers" and an accompanying methodology for identifying publishers who have editorial and financial practices which are contrary to the ideal of good research publishing practices.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The Public Library of Science is a nonprofit open-access scientific publishing project aimed at creating a library of open access journals and other scientific literature under an open content license.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The petition collected 34,000 signatures but the publishers took no strong response to the demands.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Shortly thereafter, the Public Library of Science was founded as an alternative to traditional publishing.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] HINARI is a 2002 project of the World Health Organization and major publishers to enable developing countries to access collections of biomedical and health literature online at reduced subscription costs.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The Research Works Act was a bill of the United States Congress which would have prohibited all laws which would require an open access mandate when US-government-funded researchers published their work.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The proposers of the law stated that it would "ensure the continued publication and integrity of peer-reviewed research works by the private sector".
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] This followed other similar proposed measures such as the Fair Copyright in Research Works Act.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] These attempts to limit free access to such material are controversial and have provoked lobbying for and against by numerous interested parties such as the Association of American Publishers and the American Library Association.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Critics of the law stated that it was the moment that "academic publishers gave up all pretence of being on the side of scientists." In February 2012, Elsevier withdrew its support for the bill.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Following this statement, the sponsors of the bill announced they will also withdraw their support.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In January 2012, Cambridge mathematician Timothy Gowers, started a boycott of journals published by Elsevier, in part a reaction to their support for the *Research Works Act*.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In response to an angry blog post by Gowers, the website *The Cost of Knowledge* was launched by a sympathetic reader.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] An online petition called *The Cost of Knowledge* was set up by fellow mathematician Tyler Neylon, to gather support for the boycott.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] By early April 2012, it had been signed by over eight thousand academics.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] As of mid-June 2012, the number of signatories exceeded 12,000.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In May 2012, a group of open-access activists formed the Access2Research initiative that went on to launch a petition to the White House to "require free access over the Internet to journal articles arising from taxpayer-funded research".
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The petition was signed by over 25,000 people within two weeks, which entitled it to an official response from the White House.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Since 1998, PKP has been developing free open source software platforms for managing and publishing peer-reviewed open access journals and monographs, with Open Journal Systems used by more than 7,000 active journals in 2013.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] 2013 Nobel Prize winner Randy Schekman called for a boycott of traditional academic journals including *Nature*, *Cell*, and *Science*.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Instead he promoted the open access journal *eLife*.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Initiative for Open Citations is a CrossRef initiative for improved citation analysis.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] It was supported by majority of the publishers effective from April 2017.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Diamond open access journals have been promoted as the ultimate solution to serials crisis.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Under this model, neither the authors nor the readers pay for access or publication, and the resources required to run the journal are provided by scientists on a voluntary basis, by governments or by philanthropic grants.
[src:festschrift/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Although the Diamond OA model turned out to be successful in creating a large number of journals, the percentage of publications in such journals remains low, possibly due to a low prestige of these new journals and due to concerns with their long-term viability.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Most established academic disciplines have their own journals and other outlets for publication, although many academic journals are somewhat interdisciplinary, and publish work from several distinct fields or subfields.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] There is also a tendency for existing journals to divide into specialized sections as the field itself becomes more specialized.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Along with the variation in review and publication procedures, the kinds of publications that are accepted as contributions to knowledge or research differ greatly among fields and subfields.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In the sciences, the desire for statistically significant results leads to publication bias.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Academic publishing is undergoing major changes as it makes the transition from the print to the electronic format.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Business models are different in the electronic environment.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Since the early 1990s, licensing of electronic resources, particularly journals, has been very common.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] An important trend, particularly with respect to journals in the sciences, is open access via the Internet.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In open access publishing, a journal article is made available free for all on the web by the publisher at the time of publication.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Both open and closed journals are sometimes funded by the author paying an article processing charge, thereby shifting some fees from the reader to the researcher or their funder.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Many open or closed journals fund their operations without such fees and others use them in predatory publishing.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The Internet has facilitated open access self-archiving, in which authors themselves make a copy of their published articles available free for all on the web.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Some important results in mathematics have been published only on arXiv.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The *Journal des sçavans* (later spelled *Journal des savants*), established by Denis de Sallo, was the earliest academic journal published in Europe.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Its content included obituaries of famous men, church history, and legal reports.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The first issue appeared as a twelve-page quarto pamphlet on Monday, 5 January 1665, shortly before the first appearance of the *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society*, on 6 March 1665.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The publishing of academic journals has started in the 17th century, and expanded greatly in the 19th.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] At that time, the act of publishing academic inquiry was controversial and widely ridiculed.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] It was not at all unusual for a new discovery to be announced as a monograph, reserving priority for the discoverer, but indecipherable for anyone not in on the secret: both Isaac Newton and Leibniz used this approach.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Merton, a sociologist, found that 92% of cases of simultaneous discovery in the 17th century ended in dispute.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The number of disputes dropped to 72% in the 18th century, 59% by the latter half of the 19th century, and 33% by the first half of the 20th century.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The Royal Society was steadfast in its not-yet-popular belief that science could only move forward through a transparent and open exchange of ideas backed by experimental evidence.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Early scientific journals embraced several models: some were run by a single individual who exerted editorial control over the contents, often simply publishing extracts from colleagues' letters, while others employed a group decision-making process, more closely aligned to modern peer review.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] It was not until the middle of the 20th century that peer review became the standard.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The COVID-19 pandemic hijacked the entire world of basic and clinical science, with unprecedented shifts in funding priorities worldwide and a boom in medical publishing, accompanied by an unprecedented increase in the number of publications.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Preprint servers became much more popular during the pandemic, and the Covid situation also had an impact on traditional peer-review.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The pandemic has also deepened the concentration of science-publishing in Western countries.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Of the 720000 authors of papers published about COVID-19 before August 2021, nearly 270000 were from the US, the UK, Italy or Spain.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In the 1960s and 1970s, commercial publishers began to selectively acquire "top-quality" journals that were previously published by nonprofit academic societies.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] When the commercial publishers raised the subscription prices significantly, they lost little of the market, due to the inelastic demand for these journals.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Although there are over 2,000 publishers, five for-profit companies (Reed Elsevier, Springer Science+Business Media, Wiley-Blackwell, Taylor & Francis, and SAGE) accounted for 50% of articles published in 2013.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] These factors have contributed to the "serials crisis" – total expenditures on serials increased 7.6% per year from 1986 to 2005, yet the number of serials purchased increased an average of only 1.9% per year.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Unlike most industries, in academic publishing the two most important inputs are provided "virtually free of charge".
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] These are the articles and the peer review process.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Publishers argue that they add value to the publishing process through support to the peer review group, including stipends, as well as through typesetting, printing, and web publishing.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Investment analysts, however, have been skeptical of the value added by for-profit publishers, as exemplified by a 2005 Deutsche Bank analysis which stated that "we believe the publisher adds relatively little value to the publishing process...
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Studies found the topic-specificity of scientific journals together with high impact factor expectations for career advancement some scientists have limited options in which journals to publish their work, resulting in limited competition in parts of academic publishing.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] A crisis in academic publishing is "widely perceived"; the apparent crisis has to do with the combined pressure of budget cuts at universities and increased costs for journals (the serials crisis).
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The university budget cuts have reduced library budgets and reduced subsidies to university-affiliated publishers.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The humanities have been particularly affected by the pressure on university publishers, which are less able to publish monographs when libraries can not afford to purchase them.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] For example, the ARL found that in "1986, libraries spent 44% of their budgets on books compared with 56% on journals; twelve years later, the ratio had skewed to 28% and 72%." Meanwhile, monographs are increasingly expected for tenure in the humanities.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In 2002 the Modern Language Association expressed hope that electronic publishing would solve the issue.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In 2009 and 2010, surveys and reports found that libraries faced continuing budget cuts, with one survey in 2009 finding that 36% of UK libraries had their budgets cut by 10% or more, compared to 29% with increased budgets.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In the 2010s, libraries began more aggressive cost cutting with the leverage of open access and open data.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Data analysis with open source tools like Unpaywall Journals empowered library systems in reducing their subscription costs by 70% with the cancellation of the big deal with publishers like Elsevier.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Several models are being investigated, such as open publication models or adding community-oriented features.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] It is also considered that "Online scientific interaction outside the traditional journal space is becoming more and more important to academic communication".
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In addition, experts have suggested measures to make the publication process more efficient in disseminating new and important findings by evaluating the worthiness of publication on the basis of the significance and novelty of the research finding.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In academic publishing, a paper is an academic work that is usually published in an academic journal.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] It contains original research results or reviews existing results.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Such a paper, also called an article, will only be considered valid if it undergoes a process of peer review by one or more *referees* (who are academics in the same field) who check that the content of the paper is suitable for publication in the journal.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] A paper may undergo a series of reviews, revisions, and re-submissions before finally being accepted or rejected for publication.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] This process typically takes several months.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Next, there is often a delay of many months (or in some fields, over a year) before an accepted manuscript appears.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] This is particularly true for the most popular journals where the number of accepted articles often outnumbers the space for printing.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Due to this, many academics self-archive a 'preprint' or 'postprint' copy of their paper for free download from their personal or institutional website.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Some journals, particularly newer ones, are now published in electronic form only.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Paper journals are now generally made available in electronic form as well, both to individual subscribers, and to libraries.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Journals having this delayed availability are sometimes called delayed open access journals.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Ellison in 2011 reported that in economics the dramatic increase in opportunities to publish results online has led to a decline in the use of peer-reviewed articles.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Note: Law review is the generic term for a journal of legal scholarship in the United States, often operating by rules radically different from those for most other academic journals.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Peer review is a central concept for most academic publishing; other scholars in a field must find a work sufficiently high in quality for it to merit publication.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] A group of experts reviews the manuscript regarding its originality, correctness, and relevance.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] A secondary benefit of the process is an indirect guard against plagiarism since reviewers are usually familiar with the sources consulted by the author(s).
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The origins of routine peer review for submissions dates to 1752 when the Royal Society of London took over official responsibility for *Philosophical Transactions.* However, there were some earlier examples.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] While journal editors largely agree the system is essential to quality control in terms of rejecting poor quality work, there have been examples of important results that are turned down by one journal before being taken to others.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] "Confirmatory bias" is the unconscious tendency to accept reports which support the reviewer's views and to downplay those which do not.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Experimental studies show the problem exists in peer reviewing.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The possibility of rejections of papers is an important aspect in peer review.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The evaluation of quality of journals is based also on *rejection rate*.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The best journals have the highest rejection rates (around 90–95%).
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] American Psychological Association journals' rejection rates ranged "from a low of 35 per cent to a high of 85 per cent." The complement is called "acceptance rate".
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The process of academic publishing, which begins when authors submit a manuscript to a publisher, is divided into two distinct phases: peer review and production.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The process of peer review is organized by the journal editor and is complete when the content of the article, together with any associated images, data, and supplementary material are accepted for publication.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The peer review process is increasingly managed online, through the use of proprietary systems, commercial software packages, or open source and free software.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] A manuscript undergoes one or more rounds of review; after each round, the author(s) of the article modify their submission in line with the reviewers' comments; this process is repeated until the editor is satisfied and the work is accepted.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The production process, controlled by a production editor or publisher, then takes an article through copy editing, typesetting, inclusion in a specific issue of a journal, and then printing and online publication.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Academic copy editing seeks to ensure that an article conforms to the journal's house style, that all of the referencing and labelling is correct, and that the text is consistent and legible; often this work involves substantive editing and negotiating with the authors.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] Because the work of academic copy editors can overlap with that of authors' editors, editors employed by journal publishers often refer to themselves as "manuscript editors".
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] During this process, copyright is often transferred from the author to the publisher.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In the late 20th century author-produced camera-ready copy has been replaced by electronic formats such as PDF.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The author will review and correct proofs at one or more stages in the production process.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] The proof correction cycle has historically been labour-intensive as handwritten comments by authors and editors are manually transcribed by a proof reader onto a clean version of the proof.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] In the early 21st century, this process was streamlined by the introduction of e-annotations in Microsoft Word, Adobe Acrobat, and other programs, but it still remained a time-consuming and error-prone process.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] At the end of this process, a final version of record is published.
[src:festschrift/academic-publishing] From time to time some published journal articles have been retracted for different reasons, including research misconduct.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] In British and Australian/New Zealand English, "faculty" usually refers to a sub-division of a university (usually the teaching/research staff of one or a group of departments).
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] In contrast, in North America "faculty" refers to the people who teach and research, and is distinguished from "staff", who are hired in administrative, operations, and support roles.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] For example the *Faculty Handbook* at Boston University defines faculty as Assistant, Associate, and Full Professors, those with professorial titles modified by “Research,” “Clinical,” and “of the Practice, Lecturers of all ranks, and Instructors.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] In the United States and parts of Canada, universities, community colleges and even some secondary and primary schools use the term *faculty*.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] Other institutions (e.g., teaching hospitals or not-for-profit research institutes) may likewise use the term *faculty*.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] In parts of the US, the term *academic staff* can be synonymous with just *staff*, which instead refers to staff that is not primarily involved with teaching or research.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] The higher education regulatory body of India, University Grants Commission, defines academic staff as teachers, librarians, and physical education personnel.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] In countries like the Philippines, faculty is used more broadly to refer to teaching staff of either a basic or higher education institution.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] In many universities, the members of the administration (e.g., department chairs, deans, vice presidents, presidents, and librarians) are also faculty members; many of them begin (and remain) as professors.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] These two types of faculty members are sometimes known as "nine-month faculty" and "twelve-month faculty".
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] Faculty who are paid a nine-month salary are typically allowed to seek external funds from grant agencies to partially or fully support their research activities during the summer months.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] Librarians are a special case in that they are educators like faculty who belong to degree granting departments, not necessarily administrators who have management responsibilities like Deans, Presidents, and Vice Presidents.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] Most university faculty members hold a Ph.D. or equivalent highest-level degree in their field.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] Some professionals or instructors from other institutions who are associated with a particular university (e.g., by teaching some courses or supervising graduate students) but do not hold professorships may be appointed as adjunct faculty.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] In North America, faculty is a distinct category from staff, although members of both groups are employees of the institution in question.
[src:festschrift/academic-staff] This is distinct from, for example, the British (and European, Australia, and New Zealand) usage, in which all employees of the institution are staff either on academic or professional (i.e. non-academic) contracts.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] An **acknowledgment index** (British **acknowledgement index**) is a scientometric index which analyzes acknowledgments in scientific literature and attempts to quantify their impact.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] Typically, a scholarly article has a section in which the authors acknowledge entities such as funding, technical staff, colleagues, etc. that have contributed materials or knowledge or have influenced or inspired their work.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] Like an index based on citation impact, an acknowledgment index measures influences on scientific work, but in a different sense; it measures institutional and economic influences as well as informal influences of individual people, ideas, and artifacts.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] Unlike the impact factor, it does not produce a single overall metric, but analyzes the components separately.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] However, the total number of acknowledgments to an acknowledged entity can be measured and so can the number of citations to the papers in which the acknowledgment appears.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] The ratio of this total number of citations to the total number of papers in which the acknowledge entity appears can be construed as the impact of that acknowledged entity.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] The first automated acknowledgment indexing was created in the search engine and digital library, CiteSeer.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] However, that feature is no longer supported.
[src:festschrift/acknowledgment-index] Another acknowledgment extraction and indexing system for acknowledgment was AckSeer, however, that indexing system is not available today as well.
[src:festschrift/alan-soble] Soble was born in 1947 to William and Sylvia Soble in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:festschrift/alan-soble] Early in his professional career, Soble wrote papers in areas of Ethics and Epistemology.
[src:festschrift/alan-soble] In the late 1970s he began to help articulate the fledgling specialty of the philosophy of sex, becoming one of the founding scholars and leaders of the field.
[src:festschrift/alan-soble] In 1977, while at the University of Texas in Austin, he also founded the Society for the Philosophy of Sex and Love, serving as the society's director from 1977 to 1992; the proceedings of the Society were published in 1997 as *Sex, Love, and Friendship* with Soble as editor.
[src:festschrift/alan-soble] In subsequent years, Soble edited or wrote many works in this field.
[src:festschrift/alan-soble] In late 2005 he completed the central reference work in the philosophy of sex, *Sex from Plato to Paglia*.
[src:festschrift/alan-soble] Alan Soble was Research Professor at the University of New Orleans from 1986 to 2006.
[src:festschrift/alan-soble] Soble died on March 5, 2025 at his home in Philadelphia, PA.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] AMiner (ArnetMiner) is designed to search and perform data mining operations against academic publications on the Internet, using social network analysis to identify connections between researchers, conferences, and publications.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] This allows it to provide services such as expert finding, geographic search, trend analysis, reviewer recommendation, association search, course search, academic performance evaluation, and topic modeling.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] AMiner was created as a research project in social influence analysis, social network ranking, and social network extraction.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] A number of peer-reviewed papers have been published arising from the development of the system.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] It has been in operation for more than three years, and has indexed 130,000,000 researchers and more than 265 million publications.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] The research was funded by the Chinese National High-tech R&D Program and the National Science Foundation of China.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] AMiner is commonly used in academia to identify relationships between and draw statistical correlations about research and researchers.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] It has attracted more than 10 million independent IP accesses from 220 countries and regions.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] The product has been used in Elsevier's SciVerse platform, and academic conferences such as SIGKDD, ICDM, PKDD, WSDM.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] AMiner automatically extracts the researcher profile from the web.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] It collects and identifies the relevant pages, then uses a unified approach to extract data from the identified documents.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] It also extracts publications from online digital libraries using heuristic rules.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] It integrates the extracted researchers' profiles and the extracted publications.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] It employs the researcher name as the identifier.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] A probabilistic framework has been proposed to deal with the name ambiguity problem in the integration.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] The integrated data is stored into a researcher network knowledge base (RNKB).
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] The principal other products in the area are Google Scholar, Elsevier's Scirus, and the open source project CiteSeer.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] It was initiated and created by professor Jie Tang from Tsinghua University, China.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] AMiner published several datasets for academic research purpose, including Open Academic Graph, DBLP+citation (a data set augmenting citations into the DBLP data from Digital Bibliography & Library Project), Name Disambiguation, Social Tie Analysis.
[src:festschrift/aminer-database] For more available datasets and source codes for research, please refer to.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] In academia, a ***Festschrift*** (German pronunciation: [ˈfɛst.ʃʁɪft] ⓘ; plural, *Festschriften* [ˈfɛst.ʃʁɪftn̩] ⓘ) is a book honoring a respected person, especially an academic, and presented during their lifetime.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] It generally takes the form of an edited volume, containing contributions from the honoree's colleagues, former pupils, and friends.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] The term, borrowed from German and literally meaning "celebration writing", might be translated as "celebration publication" or "celebratory (piece of) writing".
[src:festschrift/festschrift] An alternative Latin term is ***liber amicorum*** (literally: "book of friends").
[src:festschrift/festschrift] A comparable book presented posthumously is generally termed a **memorial volume** in English, or a ***Gedenkschrift*** (pronounced [ɡəˈdɛŋkʃʁɪft] ⓘ, "memorial publication") in German.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] A *Festschrift* compiled and published by electronic means on the internet is called a ***Webfestschrift*** (pronounced either [vɛp-] or [wɛb-]), a term coined by the editors of the late Boris Marshak's *Webfestschrift*, *Eran ud Aneran*, published online in October 2003.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] Originating in Germany before World War I, this European tradition of honouring special achievements in science and culture was carried to the United States by scientists who escaped the Nazis.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] In the second half of the 20th century, the practice expanded internationally.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] Its plural may be either the original *Festschriften* or anglicized as *Festschrifts*.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] A *Festschrift* contains original contributions by the honoured academic's close colleagues, often including their former doctoral students.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] It is typically published on the occasion of the honouree's retirement, significant birthday, or other notable career anniversary.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] A *Festschrift* can be anything from a slim volume to a work in several volumes.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] *Aufstieg und Niedergang der römischen Welt*, for example, began in 1972 as a *Festschrift* to commemorate the 75th birthday of Joseph Vogt, a German classical historian.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] Four volumes were planned, but it has since reached 89 volumes (including several which were planned for the next years, but put on hold in 1998).
[src:festschrift/festschrift] The essays usually relate in some way to, or reflect upon, the honouree's contributions to their scholarly field, but can include important original research by the authors.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] Many *Festschriften* also feature a *tabula gratulatoria*, an extended list of academic colleagues and friends who send their best wishes to the honouree.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] In the case of prominent academics, several *Festschriften* might be prepared by various groups of students and colleagues, particularly if the scholar made significant contributions to different fields.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] According to psychiatrist Claudio Naranjo, being selected by a prominent academic to edit a *Festschrift* can symbolize the proverbial passing of the torch.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] Thus, being designated to prepare such a collection is considered an honour in Germany.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] As Irving Louis Horowitz summarized, "*Festschriften* persist and multiply.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] Because they are not just retrospective, but prospective.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] That is to say, the *Festschrift* is a *Beruf*, a call to further work, effort, and energy, a call to the improvement of learning, of a discipline, a science, an artistic vision, or an intellectual position.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] Even in this age of mass *Festschriften*, they remain a special literary genre".
[src:festschrift/festschrift] In a 2014 review of the book *Human Expeditions: Inspired by Bruce Trigger*, Marxist archeologist Randall H.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] He suggested that because of the weaknesses, festschrifts do not sell and publishers are reluctant to publish them.
[src:festschrift/festschrift] Philosopher Alan Soble, in a review of the book *Fact and Value* in honor of MIT's philosopher Judith Jarvis Thomson, formulated – somewhat tongue-in-cheek – 13 conditions that should be satisfied by a *Festschrift*.
